CAPE TOWN - On Sunday the City of Cape Town honored the men and women of the South African National Defense Force (SANDF) that sacrificed their lives during WWI.  Remembrance Day, also known as Poppy Day around the world,and commemorates the 11th hour of the 11th day of the 11th month in 1919 when first great war finally came to an end.  The annual event and wreath-laying ceremony, which includes a gun salute, was attended by the City’s executive deputy mayor, Ian Neilson, and religious leaders, members of the South African National Defence Force (SANDF) , the South African Military Veterans’ Association, and other dignitaries.  Honouring the soldiers at the Cenotaph on Heerengracht Street , which is the city's main war memorial, for the 25 000 soldiers that died during WWI.  Members of the City’s law enforcement, fire department, traffic services and South African Police Service were also in attendance to honor the military service men and women.  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
